After l-f-c-s, where to go next.

Passing the l-f-c-s gets you to a real milestone: I can administer a linux server competently. That is a genuinely valuable skill, one that a huge fraction of the working world quietly depends on. From here the field branches in several directions, and which you choose depends on your goals.

A few natural next steps stand out. Containers are the most common, learning docker and the fundamentals of building and running images; this leads naturally toward container orchestration with kubernetes, where the certified kubernetes administrator exam is hands-on in the same spirit as the l-f-c-s. Infrastructure as code, with tools like terraform, teaches you to provision whole environments declaratively. The major cloud platforms, amazon web services, azure, and google cloud, each have their own administrator and architect certifications. If you want to go deeper into linux itself, there is a senior sibling certification, the linux foundation certified engineer. And there are well-trodden paths into security, into dev-ops with its focus on continuous delivery pipelines, and into site reliability engineering.

If your aim is the system-administrator-into-dev-ops direction, a sensible twelve-month path might run like this: spend a month or so on docker and containers, which complement the l-f-c-s beautifully; then a couple of months on kubernetes basics, working toward that hands-on administrator certification; and then a few months on infrastructure as code together with a cloud associate certification. But whatever direction you take, the single most valuable next step is hands-on time. Spin up a machine and break things on purpose. Fill the disk and recover from it. Push a process out of memory and tune the policy. Misconfigure s-s-h and lock yourself out from one window, then fix it from another. Build a service from scratch and write its unit and its timer. You will learn ten times more from one well-investigated breakage than from re-reading any chapter. Good luck on the exam, and welcome to linux.
